@arg repository-transition/identity-space
@title Repository Identity Space
@sigils [🌹/门 🌆/文]
@instantiated-by ["Researchers also use Zenodo, GitHub, Figshare, OSF," "Octopus, subject-specific repositories, and custom" "collaborative tools."]
@illustrates ["It hosts theses, publications, data, impact evidence," "rights metadata, and workflow governance."]
@instantiated-by ["We ARE Depositors, Downloaders, Governance teams," "Assessors, Archivists, Students."]
@illustrates ["The repository is not the only home of research, but it is" "the authoritative institutional expression of it."]
@instantiated-by ["We BELIEVE in Inclusivity, Confidence, Enterprising" "Creativity, Connectedness, Generosity of Spirit."]
@illustrates ["These roles bring different expectations of visibility," "compliance, openness, and credit."]
@illustrates ["Aspirations about fairness, accessibility, and collegiality" "are projected onto repository workflows."]
@illustrates ["Without articulating identity, later misalignments appear as" "political conflict, technical frustration, or cultural resistance."]

! conclusion: Our stated values and stakeholder roles form the identity space [🌹/门 🌆/文]
              from which all repository behaviours emerge — and the repository
              itself is the institutional surface where this identity becomes visible.

  + IF: A repository transition begins by clarifying the role of the repository as the institutional surface of research and mapping the stakeholders and values that shape it.

  + HOWEVER: Identity and expectations remain tacit unless explicitly mapped, and without articulating identity later misalignments appear as political conflict, technical frustration, or cultural resistance.

  + THEN: Operate an explicit move on the named axis (see substructure below); steward the pattern against the declared discipline.

Slide 1 must establish the identity inputs before moving to
                   capability outputs.

A viable repository transition must begin by clarifying the role
                 of the repository as the institutional surface of research — and
                 by mapping the stakeholders and values that shape it.

  + because: A research repository is not merely a storage system but the
             institutional surface where research practices are made public,
             accountable, and citable.

  + because: The research lifecycle at OBU spans multiple external systems.

  + because: The research ecosystem is shaped by the people who interact with it.

  + because: Institutional values establish what "good" research infrastructure
             is assumed to mean.

  + because: Identity and expectations remain tacit unless explicitly mapped.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    + Establish the identity inputs on Slide 1 before moving to capability outputs.
    + Clarify the role of the repository as the institutional surface of research.
    + Map the stakeholders and values that shape the repository.
    + Make identity and expectations explicit to prevent later misalignments.
